    <title>Combined summary - Proof of reserves - recording</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T00:14:58.485810+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-July/019215.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The bitcoin-dev mailing list recently had a discussion about proving balances held on the Lightning network and custodian proof-of-reserves. The conversation also touched on the concept of solvency in companies dealing with Bitcoin reserves and full-reserve banking. While it is not generally possible to prove balances held on the Lightning network, every channel is anchored on-chain, providing proof of existence and size. However, there are challenges with proving balances due to privacy concerns and quick changes in channel states. To address this issue, Billy Tetrud has proposed a new approach to PoR that involves creating private keys using a seed and generating a public key from this seed to represent their account.The custodian would update a map of addresses to balances, and this data would be combined with an HD wallet and hashed. The hash would be published in an on-chain transaction daily, allowing software for each user to continuously validate their balance. The discussion also covers the stability and reliability of money market funds and the need for a deeper understanding of the concepts involved in these discussions.While PoR may not insure any investment, it would greatly help people know the degree of insolvency of institutions in which they invest. However, there are no guarantees against hacks, insider or otherwise, bankruptcy, or state seizure. Overall, the conversation highlights the challenges that exist with proving Lightning network balances and the limitations of PoR. While perfect accuracy isn't possible, independent audits can attest that the PoR matches reality.A new approach to self-custody of keys has been proposed where structures are combined and hashed, and the hash is published in an on-chain transaction along with a URI where the full data can be found. This record is updated daily and users can continuously validate their account balance and verify that owned addresses have the promised funds. Users can also request a receipt for any balance update. By recording the proof of reserves on-chain, it creates a clear record that can be verified by anyone in the future, preventing custodians from changing history. This approach aims to introduce people to self-custody of keys in a light-weight manner while placing less responsibility on the user. The author encourages feedback and discussion on whether similar systems exist.</summary>
